==Overview== {{Basic Information: Japanese Deity | Name = Omotaru (淤母陀琉神) | Generation = {{ill|Seven Generations of the Divine Age|ja|神世七代}} Sixth Generation | Predecessor = {{ill|Ootonoji-Ootono be|ja|オオトノヂ・オオトノベ|lt=Itotonochi-no-Kami|lt_ja=意富斗能地神}} | Successor = {{ill|Izanagi|ja|イザナギ|lt=Izanagi-no-Kami|lt_ja=伊邪那岐神}} | Deity Type = <!-- 天神、地祇、天津神、国津神など -->{{ill|Amatsukami-Kunitsukami|ja|天津神・国津神|lt=Amatsukami|lt_ja=天津神}} | Full Name = Omotaru-no-Kami (淤母陀琉神) | Alternate Names = Omotaru, Menashison, Menashihiko, Menotarami-no-Kami | Also Known As = | Divine Rank = | Divine Function = <!-- (e.g., of the sun, the moon, mountains, or the sea) --> | Burial Place = | Father = | Mother = | Parentage = <!-- in cases of non-procreation --> | Consort = | Children = | Shrine = | Associated Shrines = {{Plainlist| * {{ill|Sixth Heavenly Deity Shrine|ja|第六天神社}} * {{ill|Kumano Hayatama Taisha|ja|熊野速玉大社}} * {{ill|Onda Shrine|ja|穏田神社}} 等 }} | Sources = {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記}}、{{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀}} 等 | Image = Omotaru kashikone shinbutsu-zue.jpg | Image Description = (『Shinbutsu Zukai』) }}
{{Basic Information: Japanese Deity | Name = Ayakashikone-no-Kami (阿夜訶志古泥神) | Generation = {{ill|Seven Generations of the Divine Age|ja|神世七代}} Sixth Generation | Predecessor = {{ill|Ootonoji-Ootono be|ja|オオトノヂ・オオトノベ|lt=Ootono no Benjin|lt_ja=大斗乃弁神}} | Successor = {{ill|Izanami|ja|イザナミ|lt=Izanami-no-Kami|lt_ja=伊邪那美神}} | Deity Type = <!-- 天神、地祇、天津神、国津神など -->{{ill|Amatsukami-Kunitsukami|ja|天津神・国津神|lt=Amatsukami|lt_ja=天津神}} | Full Name = Ayakashikone-no-Kami (阿夜訶志古泥神) | Alternate Names = Kyoukonson, Uwya Kyoujōkonson, Uwya Kashijoushin, Uwaki Kashijoushin, Ayakashikone, Kaganyohimeson, Aokashijoukonson | Also Known As = | Divine Rank = | Divine Function = <!-- (e.g., of the sun, the moon, mountains, or the sea) --> | Burial Place = | Father = | Mother = | Parentage = <!-- in cases of non-procreation --> | Consort = | Children = | Shrine = | Associated Shrines = {{Plainlist| * {{ill|Sixth Heavenly Deity Shrine|ja|第六天神社}} * {{ill|Kenotaro Shimonogi Hiko Shrine|ja|健男霜凝日子神社}} * {{ill|Onda Shrine|ja|穏田神社}} 等 }} | Sources = {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記}}、{{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀}} 等 }}
[[Image:Japanese Primordial Deities-ja.svg|thumb|right|200px|{{ill|Creation of Heaven and Earth|ja|天地開闢}} {{ill|Japanese Primordial Deities (SVG)|ja|メディア:Japanese Primordial Deities-ja.svg|lt=SVG display (compatible browsers only)|lt_ja=SVGで表示（対応ブラウザのみ）}}]]
'''Omotaru''' (淤母陀琉, also known as Menashison) ・ '''Ayakashikone'''／'''Ayakashikine''' (阿夜訶志古泥, also known as Kyoukonson) are deities appearing in {{ill|Japanese Mythology|ja|日本神話}}. {{Needs verification|{{ill|Jinmu Tennō|ja|神武天皇}} is his great-grandson|date=February 2025}}
== Overview == In the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記}}, the elder sibling is presented as '''Omotaru-no-Kami''' and the younger as '''Ayakashikone-no-Kami'''; in the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀}}, the elder is rendered as '''Menashison''' and the younger as '''Ayakashikone''' (Ayakashikine).
In the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記}}, they are regarded as the sixth-generation deities of the {{ill|Seven Generations of the Divine Age|ja|神世七代}}, with the elder, Omotaru-no-Kami, being a male deity and the younger, Ayakashikone-no-Kami, a female deity. The name "Omotaru" means "completed (i.e., without deficiency)," while "Ayakashikone" is an honorific epithet derived from "ayanikashi"—thus, they deify the perfection of the human body. {{Sfn|Kurano|2007|p=20}}{{Sfn|Nakayama|1999|p=59}}
Furthermore, Omotaru-no-Kami is interpreted by reading "淤母" as "face" and "陀琉" as "to suffice," thereby naming him to denote "a man whose facial appearance is completely satisfying." In light of the contextual correspondence with Ayakashikone-no-Kami and the enduring practice of phallic worship, his naming is also seen as a praise of the male genital form. Similarly, Ayakashikone-no-Kami is parsed with "阿夜" as an interjection, "訶志古" as the stem of "to fear," and "泥" as an honorific for persons; hence, her name implies "Oh, most venerable woman," symbolizing the awe inspired by the potent spiritual power of the female genitalia. {{Sfn|Nishimiya|2014|pp=325–326}}
In the {{ill|Medieval Period|ja|中世}}, through the syncretism of Shinto and Buddhism ({{ill|Shinbutsu-shūgō|ja|神仏習合}}), these deities—as the sixth-generation in the {{ill|Seven Generations of the Divine Age|ja|神世七代}}—came to be regarded as the manifestation ({{ill|Suijaku|ja|垂迹}}) of the {{ill|Sixth Heavenly Demon King|ja|天魔|lt=Sixth Heavenly Demon King|lt_ja=第六天魔王}}, the highest rank of the {{ill|Six Desire Heavens|ja|六欲天}} in the Buddhist desire realm. They were especially venerated in {{ill|Shugendō|ja|修験道}}. With the separation of Shinto and Buddhism in the {{ill|Meiji Era|ja|明治}} ({{ill|Shinbutsu Bunri|ja|神仏分離}}), many temples ({{ill|Buddhist Temple|ja|寺}}) enshrining the Sixth Heavenly Demon King were converted into shrines ({{ill|Shinto Shrine|ja|神社}}), and were renamed as, for example, {{ill|Sixth Heavenly Deity Shrine|ja|第六天神社}}, Koro Shrine, and {{ill|Menashi Shrine|ja|面足神社}}.
